Science of The Total Environment

Volume 864, 15 March 2023, 161153

Redox oscillations destabilize and mobilize colloidal soil organic carbon

Author links open overlay panel, , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2022.161153Get rights and content

Highlights

  • •

    Soil columns were induced to cumulative redox oscillation cycles.

  • •

    Release of OC was increased by 4-fold and 54-fold in the SO and SA columns.

  • •

    Colloid (> 100 nm) concentration increased from 7 % to 40 % between 1st and 2nd ROs.

  • •

    RO cycles enhanced the formation of nano and microaggregates.

  • •

    Cumulative RO cycles released more microbial-derived C.

Abstract

The onset of oxic-anoxic events in soil induces biogeochemical processes that may have profound influences on the fate and transport of soil organic carbon (OC). An 18-wk long laboratory soil column study was conducted to investigate the influence of static oxic (SO), static anoxic (SA), or redox oscillation (RO) events on the release of OC. Column leachate samples were collected after 9-wk and 18-wk of incubations and separated into dissolved (<2.3 nm), natural nanoparticle (2.3–100 nm), fine colloid (100–450 nm), and particulate (> 450 nm) fractions that were characterized through spectrofluorometric analyses. The concentration of released OC from different treatment columns followed the order of SA > RO > SO. After 9-wk, total OC concentrations in the leachate samples were increased by 4-fold and 54-fold in the SO and SA columns compared to the time-zero control columns, respectively. However, after 18-wk, the released amount of OC doubled in SO but decreased by 50 % in SA columns compared to the 9-wk incubation samples. The RO columns had intermediate OC concentrations between the SO and SA treatments. The RO events further led to widely varied dynamics in the release and molecular composition of the size-fractionated OC compared to static conditions, indicating the effects of redox oscillation on the organo-mineral association in soil. The wide variations in the aromaticity of OC released after the 1st and 2nd RO events further support the notion that alternating redox processes regulate OC cycling differently than the SO or SA condition. The observed increase in fine colloid and particulate OC fractions (i.e., >100 nm) from 7 % to 40 % between 1st and 2nd RO suggests the clustering of nanoaggregates and/or formation of colloidal size aggregates. The composition of the released OC as influenced by redox fluctuations provides a baseline for the size continuum of soil OC and its potential ecological and environmental roles.

1. Introduction

Wetlands contain a disproportionately large amount of terrestrial OC (535 GT C, ∼30 % of terrestrial C) (Mitsch and Gosselink, 2007). Climate change is a major threat to these wetlands as it can adversely affect the amplitude and periodicity of wetting-drying cycles due to the predicted increases in warming and precipitation events. Any changes in the stability and turnover of wetland C pool induced by geochemical and climatic factors will have significant impacts on global C cycles (Doetterl et al., 2015). Increasing evidence supports the idea that soil organic matter (SOM) is an ecosystem-level property (Schmidt et al., 2011) and the association between minerals and SOM is one of the key C stabilization mechanisms (Baldock and Skjemstad, 2000; Kleber et al., 2007; Wagai and Mayer, 2007). Redox conditions as influenced by hydrological and biogeochemical perturbations in seasonally-flooded wetlands can influence the stability and storage of soil C stocks, 90 % of which is in intimate association with minerals (Baisden et al., 2002; Basile-Doelsch et al., 2007; Crow et al., 2007).

In redox-sensitive environments such as wetlands, the stability of organo-mineral associations is controlled directly by their structural and chemical properties (Guggenberger and Kaiser, 2003; Kaiser et al., 2002; Kalbitz et al., 2005; Mikutta et al., 2007) and indirectly by shifts in porewater chemistry, e.g., pH, pE, ionic strength (IS), and ionic composition (Bunn et al., 2002). Adsorption and coprecipitation of SOM with Fe- and Al- oxides and hydroxides and formation of bridging complexes with Ca (Mikutta et al., 2007; Weng et al., 2005) can alter the size, crystallinity, and reactivity of newly formed organo-mineral complexes (Eusterhues et al., 2014; Mikutta et al., 2014; Shimizu et al., 2013). Mineral colloids (1–1000 nm; Vold and Vold, 1983), having very large specific surface areas and reactive charge densities, can disperse under anaerobic conditions and serve as a significant transport vector of associated OC through the vadose zone (de Jonge et al., 1998; Sprague et al., 2000; Villholth et al., 2000).

Reduction-oxidation (redox) processes promote soil colloid mobilization through (i) reductive dissolution of Mn- and Fe- oxyhydroxides that hold aggregates together and (ii) inter-particle electrostatic repulsion between like-charged particles due to the concomitant changes in pH (Bunn et al., 2002; Grybos et al., 2009; Heil and Sposito, 1993; Suarez et al., 1984; Thompson et al., 2006a). The colloids released as a result of redox oscillations have varied compositions and sizes (Guo and Santschi, 2007). Colloidal particles have unique reactivity and mobility and thus they behave differently from <1 nm or > 1000 nm fractions (Afsar et al., 2020; Baalousha et al., 2011; Tang et al., 2022). Compared to solutes, some colloids can travel at a higher velocity owing to their size and charge exclusion effects and hence bypassing the less mobile water domains in small pores and narrow transport pathways (Xie et al., 2014; Keller and Auset, 2007). Moreover, the bioavailability of OM changes by forming a biopolymer in the colloidal phase (Benner and Amon, 2015). Despite the importance and uniqueness of colloids, their role in OC fate in soil, including wetlands, remains largely unaccounted. The use of the operational definition that classifies dissolved OM (DOM) as <450 nm places many colloidal OC as “dissolved” solutes. This potentially leads to an inaccurate interpretation of ecosystem function OC in SOC storage, which has been argued previously (Guo and Santschi, 2007; Rod et al., 2020a, Rod et al., 2020b; Yan et al., 2018). Therefore, more detailed redox-dependent size delineation and quantification of mobile SOM is necessary.

The shifts in OM molecular composition and the underlying mechanisms of organo-mineral associations are seen as a dominant process in the stabilization of soil OM. For example, recent studies with new molecular and spectroscopic techniques have revealed that microbial-derived OC is more decomposition-resistant than plant-derived components (Amelung et al., 2008; Gleixner, 2013; Grandy and Neff, 2008; Miltner et al., 2012) and is stabilized via organo-mineral complexation (Baldock and Skjemstad, 2000; Kleber et al., 2015). Therefore, the holistic underlying mechanisms of organo-mineral interactions are of great research interest. According to the two-dimensional view of organo-mineral associations, OM assembles uniformly as a function of distance from mineral surfaces (Possinger et al., 2020). The more recently proposed three-dimensional view (Kleber and Johnson, 2010) suggests that mineral-OM microaggregates form around microbial metabolites. Thus, the fluxes and accumulation of soil OM, which are in part controlled by redox conditions, depend on the dynamics of sorption and desorption as well as microbial processing and subsequent dissolution of OC (Kalbitz et al., 2000). Despite the significant role that mobile OC plays in the global C cycle, a comprehensive understanding of the colloid-OC dynamics and the molecular composition of OC in different size fractions is lacking.

We conducted a soil column study to assess the influence of redox conditions, including static oxic, static anoxic, and oscillating oxic-anoxic on the concentration and molecular composition of size-fractionated OC in the mobile phase (< 1000 nm). Columns were systematically maintained under static or oscillating oxic-anoxic events for 18 wks; leachate samples were collected at two-time intervals (9-wk and 18-wk) and were size-fractionated using differential centrifugation and ultrafiltration. The unique aspects of this work relative to prior studies include 1) redox oscillations were induced in column-flow mode rather than through batch incubation and 2) concentration and molecular composition of aqueous OC were quantified and characterized for multiple colloidal size fractions, i.e., dissolved (< 2.3 nm), natural nanoparticles (NNP, 2.3–100 nm), fine colloid (100–450 nm), and particulate (> 450 nm). We selected the size ranges based on the following rationale: 1) 450 nm is the most commonly used size cutoff in studies of soil colloids, colloids in surface and ground waters, and particulate vs. dissolved organic matter in these systems; 2) 220 nm is commonly used in marine systems to exclude microbial cells (Chen et al., 2004) and it is the cutoff size-range between the fine and coarse clay fractions (Ranville et al., 2005); 3) 100 nm is the upper size limit used to define nanoparticles; and 4) 2.3 nm differentiates particles from truly dissolved fractions, which is commonly used for studying estuarine colloidal C (Guo and Santschi, 2007). Total OC concentration, UV–visible absorbance, and fluorescence excitation-emission matrices (EEMs) were measured to elucidate size-dependent heterogeneity in the concentration and molecular composition of mobile OC.

2. Materials and methods

2.1. Soil description

Soil samples were collected from the top 0–15 cm layer along the rim of a freshwater wetland located in the White Clay Creek (WCC) watersheds, Delaware, USA. The rim is the seasonally-saturated section of the wetland that is characterized by having an aerobic near-surface horizon for part of the year. The WCC is one of the four major watersheds in the 1463 km2 6th-order Christina River Basin - a part of the larger 33,700 km2 Delaware River Basin. The respective mean annual precipitation and water flow rates are 111.76 cm and 50.8 cm per year, indicating relatively plentiful groundwater recharge to stream base flow (Narvaez and Homsey, 2016). Based on the Delaware Climate Change Impact Assessment Report (2014), the average precipitation is expected to increase by 10 % with more frequent and intense heavy precipitation events in Delaware over the next century. The wetland is classified as a permanently-saturated emergent toe-slope wetland (USDA-NRCS, 2018). The dominant vegetation in most of the wetland is emergent (perennial herbaceous species). The soil samples for the experiments were collected from the seasonally saturated zone along the rim of the wetlands, where the plant community is classified as a mixed deciduous forest. Soil samples were air-dried, passed through a 2 mm sieve, and immediately repacked in acrylic columns. The texture of the soil is silt loam with an initial total OC content of 4.98 %. A summary of the soil's chemical composition is listed in Table S1 in Supplemental Information (SI). Based on a U.S. Geological Survey report (1984), the soil predominantly contains quartz minerals in the sand and silt fractions, and the clay fraction is composed of kaolinite and illite in a 7:3 ratio.

2.2. Preparation of soil columns

Columns were made of hard acrylic (inner Ø: 7.5 cm, L: 35 cm), with a nylon mesh (bubbling pressure: 40 mbar) and a porous plastic disk (pore Ø: ∼ 3.0 mm) at the bottom to support the packed soil. A schematic diagram of the column set-up is shown in Fig. 1. Each column was packed by adding soil layer by layer in 1 cm increments to minimize packing heterogeneity. Each layer was gently pressed to have a bulk density of 1.23 g cm−3 (∼1.3 kg of soil in each column to a total height of 24 cm), leaving a headspace of 11 cm. Two platinum redox probes of 7 cm × 0.8 cm (L × Ø, Paleo Terra, Netherlands) were installed horizontally at 10 cm and 17 cm depths in each column to monitor soil redox status for the entire duration of the experiments.

2.3. Redox oscillation experiment

A total of six soil columns were prepared to run duplicate experiments under three redox conditions for 18-wk, including (1) static oxic (SO), (2) static anoxic (SA), and (3) alternate oxic and anoxic for two complete redox oscillations (RO). One RO event represents a 4-wk of oxic followed by a 5-wk of anoxic conditions. No supplemental C was added to those columns. To maintain SO or SA conditions, respective columns were either flushed intermittently with O2 gas or with N2 gas for 4 h at the beginning of the experiments, followed by saturation with degassed 2.0 mM NaCl electrolyte solution (Thompson et al., 2006a). For the SO columns, the electrolyte solution was added after 9-wk or 18-wk incubations and immediately leached. The solution was added in an upward flow mode at a velocity of 1 mL min−1 for ∼20 h using a peristaltic pump until the standing water height reached 11 cm above the soil surface. The flow rate was selected based on our preliminary experiments to ensure the maximum saturation of the soil columns by the capillary rise method and to minimize entrapped gas bubbles (Klute, 1986). The specific height of ponding water was chosen to ensure that at least 1 pore volume (PV) of leachate could be collected. For the columns used in this study, 1 PV was calculated to be 573 mL at a bulk density of 1.23 g cm−3, assuming a particle density of 2.65 g cm−3 (Singh and Kanwar, 1991). The schematic diagram of the experimental procedure is illustrated in Fig. S1.

After 9-wk incubations, all three sets of soil columns were drained completely, incubated for another 9-wk under their respective conditions, i.e., SO, SA, or RO, and then leached again. An additional set of duplicate oxic (not incubated) time-zero columns was prepared, following the procedure described above, and leached immediately to serve as a time-zero control. These time-zero columns were not exposed to any redox changes before leaching.

Leachate samples from each column were collected using a fraction collector (Foxy Jr., Teledyne Isco, Lincoln, NE). Fraction collectors were placed inside a glove bag under continuous flushing with N2 for anoxic columns. Four 10-mL leachate samples, each was transferred to a 15-mL centrifuge tube for size fractionation into four size fractions using a Sorvall centrifuge (Thermo Scientific) with a F13s-14*50Y rotor: < 450 nm (7 min at 680 × g rcf or 2000 rpm), < 220 nm (10 min at 1860 × g rcf or 3300 rpm), < 100 nm (11 min at 8370 × g rcf or 7000 rpm), and < 2.3 nm (∼10 kDa) and at 4 °C. The centrifugation speed and time to achieve the targeted particle sizes were calculated from the Stokes' law (Gimbert et al., 2005) assuming spherical particles and particle density of 2.65 g cm−3 (See SI, S1) (Murphy et al., 1993; Taylor et al., 1992). While using the centrifugation method can avoid the errors caused by pore-clogging associated with filtration, the assumptions of the Stoke's law do not account for the heterogeneity of particle composition and irregular particle shapes, which are the drawbacks of the centrifugation method. For example, when assuming a particle density of 2.65 g cm−3, particles composed of mostly organic materials, which have lower than 2.65 g cm−3 density and are non-spherical, preferentially remain in the supernatant compared with the mineral particles with the same size. The <2.3 nm fraction was separated using an ultrafiltration system (Amicon® stirred cell) with Ultracel® 10 kDa membrane ultrafiltration discs (EMD Millipore Corporation), inside the glove bag for anoxic samples. In this study, we denote particles in the size range of 100–450 nm, 2.3–100 nm, and < 2.3 nm as the fine colloid, NNP, and dissolved C fractions, respectively.

2.4. Sample analyses

2.4.1. Chemical analyses

The pH, Eh, and electrical conductivity (EC) of the leachate samples were measured with corresponding probes (Fisher Scientific, Hampton, NH). Ionic Strength (IS) was calculated from the measured EC values, IS = 0.013 x EC, where the unit of EC is ds m−1 (Alva et al., 1991; Morrisson et al., 1990). Iron (II) concentration of the leachate samples was measured following the ferrozine method (Stookey, 1970) using a UV–visible spectrophotometer at a limit of quantification (LOQ) of 0.1 mg L−1. Although Fe (II) and Fe (III) could form complexes with organic and inorganic compounds and thus potentially interfere with UV–Vis measurements, Viollier et al. (2000) demonstrated that Fe complexation with Suwannee river OM did not significantly underestimate measured Fe content, even in organic-rich water (e.g., 25 mg L−1). Organic carbon concentrations (total, < 450 nm, < 220 nm, < 100 nm, and < 2.3 nm) were measured with a total organic carbon (TOC) analyzer (Apollo 9000 TOC analyzer, Tekmar, Dohrmann) at a detection limit of 4 μg L−1 and used to calculate C concentrations in >450 nm, 220–450 nm, 100–220 nm, and 2.3–100 nm size fractions. The turbidity of the leachate samples was determined using a nephelometer (HACH, Loveland, CO) in nephelometric turbidity units (NTU), which was then converted into colloid concentrations using the concentration-turbidity regression equation developed by Yan et al. (2017) based on the measurements of 37 soil samples [concentration = (0.94 ± 0.02) × Turbidity, R2 = 0.86]. Nephelometric turbidimetry has been widely used in studies of sediment and colloid transport that represent the presence of both mineral and organic particles (de Jonge et al., 2004; Minella et al., 2008; Rügner et al., 2013). Yan et al. (2017) observed significant correlations between turbidity and colloid concentration for different size fractions using samples collected from soils across the U.S., while the effects of particle composition and OM are largely negligible. The colloid concentration determined using nephelometric turbidity in this study includes contributions of both mineral and organic colloids in different redox columns.

2.4.2. Spectrofluorometric analyses

Molar absorption spectra were measured with a double-beam Shimadzu UV–vis spectrophotometer (Shimadzu Inc.) using a 1 cm path-length quartz cuvette. The specific ultraviolet absorbance (SUVA254, L mg C−1 m−1) was calculated for each size fraction by normalizing the UV absorbance at 254 nm (A254), an indicator of SOM aromaticity (Weishaar et al., 2003; Zsolnay et al., 1999), with its corresponding OC concentration. Possible interference of Fe with SUVA254 measurement was corrected using the Fe (III) absorption coefficient of 6.53 × 10−2 L mg−1 cm−1 (Poulin et al., 2014). Iron (III) concentrations of multiple samples were measured using inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (Thermo Scientific iCAP TQ ICP-MS). We only considered the interference from Fe(III) because Poulin et al. (2014) found negligible interference of Fe (II) on UV absorbance at 254 nm.

Three-dimensional fluorescence scans were also performed on the leachate samples using a Horiba Jobin Yvon Fluoromax-P Spectrofluorometer (Horiba Scientific, Edison, NJ, USA). Each sample was transferred from a sealed vial to a quartz cuvette, immediately closed to minimize direct exposure to air, and analyzed under anoxic conditions. Fluorescence EEMs spectra were measured with scanning emission wavelengths from 300 to 550 nm at 2-nm increments by varying the excitation wavelengths from 270 to 450 nm at 5-nm intervals. The integration time for sample collection was set at 0.30 s. Results were normalized to the integrated intensity of the Raman scattering band of ultrapure water (Milli-Q, Millipore) at 350 nm excitation wavelength (Cory and McKnight, 2005). Samples were diluted to an A254 between 0.1 and 0.2 cm−1 to avoid inner filter effects, i.e., re-absorption of fluorescence light (Miller et al., 2010; Green and Blough, 1994; Ohno, 2002). Fluorescence properties of size-fractionated SOM collected after 1st and 2nd RO were assessed by determining three indices: humification index (HIX), biological index (BIX), and fluorescence index (FI). The humification index, similar to SUVA254 as an indicator of SOM's aromaticity, was determined as the area under the emission range of 300–345 nm, for excitation at 254 nm (Ohno, 2002). The biological index, a parameter that indicates the degree of microbial decomposition, was calculated as the signal ratio of emission at 380 nm divided by the maximum emission between 420 and 435 nm for excitation at 310 nm. Fluorescence index, the signal ratio of emission 470–520 nm at excitation 370 nm, differentiates between microbial and terrestrial origins of OM (∼ 1.8 for the microbial origin and ∼ 1.2 for terrestrial origin) (Cory and McKnight, 2005; McKnight et al., 2001). The EEMs scans were fitted to a 13-component parallel factor (PARAFAC) model (Fig. S2). Four of the 13 components (Component 3, 5, 8, and 13) were studied in detail to elucidate the molecular properties of size-fractionated OM. All the optical and fluorescence indices used in this study are summarized and explained in Table S2.

2.4.3. Statistical analyses

Pearson's correlation coefficients between solution pH, pE, and Fe (II) concentration and colloid and OC concentrations were obtained using Origin (OriginLab Northampton, MA). In addition, linear regression was performed between pH and pE.

3. Results

3.1. Soil and solution chemistry

Soil redox potential (Eh) did not change appreciably with depth in each soil column, although the values varied among different treatments (Table 1). In comparison to the time-zero control columns, Eh values became more positive (i.e., more oxic) in the SO columns but more negative (i.e., more anoxic) in the SA columns after incubations. For the RO columns, alternate oxic-anoxic conditions decreased Eh values compared to the control but had intermediate values between the SO and SA columns. For longer incubations (i.e., after 18-wk), Eh values decreased in SO, increased in RO, and were more constant in SA columns at both depths.

The values of pH, Eh (pE), and IS of the leachate samples from all the soil columns are summarized in Fig. 2a-d. For SO columns, pH, Eh (pE), and IS of the leachate samples did not change significantly from their initial values at time zero. For the SA columns, solution pH increased with increasing anoxic incubation period to 7.95 ± 0.10 after 18-wk. On the other hand, Eh continuously decreased under SA conditions and reached −180 ± 30 mV after 18-wk. For RO columns, pH increased after the 1st RO and then decreased after the 2nd RO. Opposite to the changes in pH, Eh initially decreased and then increased following the 1st and 2nd ROs, respectively. The RO columns had more variable IS over time compared to the SO and SA columns. Except for the 1st RO cycle, IS values did not change appreciably among different treatments. After 1st RO, IS increased to 16.74 ± 0.40 mM, indicating a minor effect of static oxic or anoxic incubations on it.

Iron (II) concentrations in the leachate samples from the SO, SA, and RO columns differed greatly. The concentrations were below the detection limit (0.001 mM) in the leachates of the control and SO columns (both SO-9 and SO-18), were the highest after 9-wk in the SA columns (5.56 ± 0.32 mM) and then decreased after 18-wk incubations. The concentration was 2.98 ± 0.94 mM after 1st RO and decreased to 0.30 ± 0.01 mM after 2nd RO. The differences in Fe (II) concentration are consistent with the changes in pH and Eh (Fig. 2d).

3.2. Release of colloids and OC

Colloid concentrations, [colloid], in the leachate samples from all columns are shown in Fig. 3. The amount of colloids released from the SO columns after both 9-wk and 18-wk did not change appreciably compared to that from the control columns, but the concentration increased by 4 to 5-fold in the SA columns. Redox oscillations significantly increased colloid release after the 1st RO but decreased after the 2nd RO to values similar to those from the control and SO columns. Overall, the colloid release is positively correlated with solution pH (Pearson's r = 0.90**) and dissolved Fe (II) concentration (Pearson's r = 0.76), but negatively correlated with Eh (Pearson's r = 0.87*) (Fig. S2). Although the p-value for the correlation between colloid and Fe(II) concentrations was <0.05, we would not dismiss the possibility of iron reduction on colloid release.

A trend of increasing TOC concentration was detected in the leachate samples of incubated vs oxic time-zero columns (Fig. 4a-g). After both 9-wk and 18-wk incubations, SO column leachates had lower TOC concentrations compared to SA columns, indicating some release of OC induced by oxic conditions. After 9-wk, SO incubation led to a 4-fold increase in TOC whereas SA incubation had 54-fold increase in TOC release, compared to the control columns. During the 2nd 9-wk incubation, while OC release from the SO columns almost doubled, it decreased by 50 % in the SA columns compared to the prior 9-wk incubations. TOC concentrations were lower after 1st and 2nd RO cycles than the SA columns incubated for the same periods. Similar to the trends observed for colloid release, TOC concentrations in the leachates of all columns were also positively correlated with pH (Pearson's r = 0.69) and Fe (II) concentration (Pearson's r = 0.87) and negatively correlated with pE (Pearson's r = −0.66), although all the relationships were not statistically significant (Fig. S4).

Size-fractionated OC concentrations and their normalized values to the TOC content (from here on called “relative C content”) in the column leachates are summarized in Fig. 4(a-g). Consistent with TOC release, size-fractionated OC concentrations were higher in the incubated than oxic time-zero columns. Fig. 4 also shows that the NNP and dissolved fractions had the highest OC concentrations in all the incubated columns regardless of redox conditions. Whereas OC concentrations in all the size fractions gradually increased from time zero to 18-wk in the SO columns, the concentrations initially increased between time zero to 9-wk and then decreased after 18-wk in the SA columns. After 9-wk incubation, OC concentration in the particulate, fine colloid, NNP, and dissolved fractions increased by 2 to 4-fold in the SO columns and 16 to 50-fold in the SA columns in comparison to the oxic time-zero columns. After 18-wk, OC release associated with different size fractions was increased by only 1 to 2-fold in the SO columns and decreased by 50 % in the SA columns to the prior 9-wk incubations. For example, the dissolved OC concentration increased from 33.43 ± 12.19 mg L−1 to 56.30 ± 5.94 mg L−1 between 9-wk to 18-wk during oxic incubation. For the same time interval, the concentration decreased from 447.09 ± 33.40 mg L−1 to 207.01 ± 41.60 mg L−1 under anoxic incubation.

Redox oscillation had more complex and varied dynamics in the size-fractionated OC release compared to the static ones (Fig. 4). The release of OC decreased in the NNP and dissolved fractions after the 2nd vs 1st RO events. The relative OC content of the NNP and dissolved fractions decreased from 32 ± 4 % and 62 ± 4 % after 1st RO to 12 ± 5 % and 49 ± 8 % after 2nd RO, respectively. In contrast, the relative OC content in the larger size fractions (i.e., > 100 nm) increased from ∼3 % to 26 % (>450 nm) and ∼ 4 % to 14 % (100–220 nm and 220–450 nm combined) after 2nd vs 1st RO cycles. Here, the OC concentrations in the particulate and fine colloid fractions increased by ∼8-fold and 3-fold, respectively, following the 2nd RO in comparison to the 1st RO cycles. During the 9 to 18-wk incubation period, such size-dependent variations in OC concentrations were absent in the SO and SA columns.

3.3. Optical and fluorescence properties of OC

Specific UV absorbance at 254 nm (SUVA254) and % aromatic C content in different size fractions are summarized in Fig. 5. Time-zero samples from the control columns had SUVA254 values ranging from 0.65 to 2.30 L mg−1C m−1, corresponding to an aromatic OC content of 8–19 %. Samples from SO columns always had lower aromatic C percentages (8–11 %) than those from the SA columns (20–30 %) after both 9-wk and 18-wk incubations. Similar to the changes in size-fractionated OC concentrations, RO events led to more complex and distinct variations in OC composition in the leachate samples. Redox oscillation induced the release of more highly aromatic OC after the 1st than the 2nd RO cycles (Fig. 5). After 9-wk, both the RO and SA released OC having higher aromatic molecular composition than the time-zero columns. In contrast, OC aromaticity was still above 25 % in the SA column leachate samples after 18-wk incubation while the values dropped to below 15 % after 2nd RO cycle.

The molecular composition of the size-fractionated leachate samples collected from the time-zero columns and after the 1st and 2nd ROs was characterized using additional fluorescence indices and the PARAFAC analyses based on EEMs data (Fig. 6). At time zero, the OC in the leachates had the highest HIX, % C5, and % protein-like fluorescence values and the lowest BIX, FI, and % C3 values. Following the 2nd RO, HIX, % C5, and % protein-like fluorescence values decreased and BIX, FI, and % C3 values increased. Among size-fractionated particles, fluorescent C components did not differ widely within the size range between 2.3 and 450 nm but significantly changed at <2.3 nm fraction. We did not conduct EEMs analyses on the leachate samples from SO or SA columns as we observed consistent changes in SUVA254 values between 9-wk and 18-wk incubations.

4. Discussion

4.1. Effect of redox oscillations on the release of soil colloids

Changes in redox conditions led to the observed changes in Fe (II) concentration, Eh, and pH (Fig. 2) of the leachate samples, which are consistent with iron reduction reactions in soils (Lindsay, 1979):FeOH3soils+3H++e−=Fe2+aq+3H2O

The Eh-pH values and the corresponding changes in Fe (II) concentrations due to changes in redox conditions are strongly correlated with the critical Eh-pH of Fe reduction in soils. As shown in previous studies, the critical values for iron reduction are 300 mV at pH 5, between 300 and 100 mV at pH 6–7, and around −100 mV at pH 8 (Gotoh and Patrick, 1972; Patrick and Henderson, 1981). In this study, the observed increase in pH following SA or RO events is due to the consumption of protons during the reduction of NO3−, Mn, and Fe (Ponnamperuma, 1972). Greater colloid release with increasing pH is likely caused by increasing dispersion of soil colloids at higher pHs. Typically, SOM has a lower point of zero charges (PZC, < 4) than the Fe and Al (hydr)oxides (PZC: ∼ 6–9) (Chorover and Sposito, 1995). As the pH increases above the point of zero charges, hydroxyl functional groups deprotonate and generate repulsive forces between particles that can enhance the dispersion of soil colloids.

The influence of pH, Eh, IS, and reductive dissolution of Fe (II) on colloid release can further be evaluated by their corresponding changes at different incubation periods (i.e., 9-wk vs 18-wk). The increase in colloid concentration in SA-18 columns with pH despite a decrease in Fe (II) concentration points that rising pH is the dominant factor in releasing OC under SA condition (Grybos et al., 2009; Thompson et al., 2006a). The strong positive relationship observed between pH and colloid release (p < 0.01, Fig. S2) supports this conclusion. By comparison, colloid release from the RO columns is consistent with changes in both pH and reductive dissolution of Fe-oxyhydroxides. It implies that in addition to pH, reductive dissolution of Fe also plays a dominant role to mobilize substantial quantities of colloids and OC under RO cycles. The significantly higher release of >100 nm particles after 2nd RO cycle further points to the dominant role of Fe reduction events on colloid release (Fig. 4). Reductive dissolution can dissolve Fe oxide coatings that can bind larger aggregates and facilitate particle dispersion (Afsar et al., 2020; Grybos et al., 2009; Ryan and Gschwend, 1994; Thompson et al., 2006a). Buettner et al. (2014) observed dispersion of large colloidal OC (60–430 nm) due to iron reduction in batch incubation studies. We did not see any consistent effect of IS on colloid release except in the 1st RO event. Here, we posit that the role of IS on colloid release was masked by other factors depending on the overall environmental condition of the soil columns.

Although we do not have direct evidence, we assume that a greater number of redox oscillations can lead to (1) loss of more easily reduced amorphous Fe minerals and (2) increased crystallinity of Fe minerals in the soil. The less crystalline, amorphous Fe minerals were likely reduced and subsequently, more soluble Fe fractions were leached after 9-wk than 18-wk incubations from the RO and SA columns (Miller et al., 2001). The increase in colloid stability under redox fluctuations (Thompson et al., 2006a) might decrease the overall colloid release from RO columns after 18-wk than 9-wk incubations. This observation is consistent with the finding recently reported by Possinger et al. (2020). They observed an increase in Fe crystallinity due to the loss of amorphous Fe-organic complexes at high water-saturation frequency (5 saturation cycles per 30 days) in the Hubbard Brook Experimental Forest soils.

The differences in Eh values found between 1st and 2nd RO (i.e., limited development of reducing conditions after the 2nd RO) may be attributed to the use of alternate terminal electron acceptors, e.g., nitrate (NO3−) and the limited availability of decomposable OC during the 2nd RO. Nitrate can be produced during the intermediate oxic period through ammonium oxidation (NH4+ → NO2− → NO3−), which can prevent lowering the redox potential during the 2nd RO events. In our study, the rapid depletion of O2 by N2 gas at the initiation of the reducing half-cycle in the columns could enhance NO3− denitrification thus stabilizing the redox potential at approximately +200 mV. Strong inverse relationship between Eh and pH values in the leachate samples clearly points to the significant role of Eh in controlling soil pH. Reddy and Patrick (1975) reported that NO3− produced under prolonged intermediate oxic conditions, which is comparable to the lapsed time between 1st and 2nd reducing half-cycle in our study, prevented significant changes in redox potential during successive reducing events.

4.2. Effect of redox oscillations on the release of OC

The higher OC release after both 9-wk and 18-wk anoxic incubation in comparison to the SO and RO conditions (Fig. 4) ascribes to a decrease in sorption capacity for OC on mineral surfaces, particularly with Fe minerals. The observed OC release triggered by anoxic conditions is consistent with the results from previous studies (Fiedler and Kalbitz, 2003; Grybos et al., 2009; Kögel-Knabner et al., 2010). As soil OC exists largely in complexes with soil minerals, the same mechanisms, such as microbial reduction of Fe minerals and the concomitant changes in solution pH, that are responsible for colloid release under anoxic conditions can also lead to the release of OC (Gu et al., 1994; Shimizu et al., 2013). Significantly high percentages of NNP in all the column leachate samples further underestimate the colloidal phase and its retention and transport functions in C cycling (Afsar, 2020; Guo and Santschi, 2007; Yan et al., 2018). In a batch incubation study, Afsar et al. (2020) further observed an increase in C percentages with decreasing particle sizes. Therefore, the operational cutoff size range of dissolved OC (<450 nm) is incomplete and needs further revision.

4.3. Mineral-SOM interactions as a function of redox oscillation

The higher OC concentrations and their corresponding higher SUVA254 values in the leachate samples suggest a selective release of aromatic-rich OC from the SA columns (Fig. 4, Fig. 5). In comparison, the much lower SUVA254 values (<15 %) in the SO columns implies that the mobile OC in these columns was mostly hydrophilic in nature (e.g., aliphatic C) as light absorption is inversely proportional to the soil hydrophilic OC fractions (Dilling and Kaiser, 2002). The release of highly aliphatic and hydrophilic OC under oxic conditions echoes with previous findings that SOC having higher hydrophobicity and aromatic C content (∼ 35 %) is preferentially removed from the soil solution due to their strong affinity to the surface hydroxyl groups of Fe and Mn oxyhydroxides (Kaiser et al., 1996; Kaiser and Zech, 2000; Qualls and Haines, 1991; Ussiri and Johnson, 2004). Hydrophobic OC can suppress or even displace indigenous hydrophilic substances from soil sorption sites (Kaiser et al., 1996). Our finding is further supported by the study of Rouwane et al. (2018) in wetland soil, where they observed an increase in the polar constituents of aromatic structures in solubilized organic compounds under reducing conditions. The higher release of aromatic C compounds upon abiotic reduction was also reported by Adhikari and Yang (2015). The shift in the composition of released OC implies a contrasting stability and sorption behavior of aliphatic and aromatic OC under an oxic vs anoxic environment. The high susceptibility of aromatic OC to release under anoxic conditions may be caused by the steric effect of the aromatic rings, which leads them to reside on the outer surface of organo-mineral complexes (Adhikari and Yang, 2015). In contrast to aromatic C, more flexible aliphatic C can bind to soil minerals' inner layers and be preserved by the outer organic matter layer (Gao et al., 2019; Kleber et al., 2007).

The differences in the molecular composition of mobile OC between 1st and 2nd RO events provide evidence for the effects of redox oscillation processes on the organo-mineral association in soil. The observed low SUVA254 values after 2nd RO suggest that microbial-derived, aliphatic OC compounds can represent a significant source of mobile OC under cumulative redox oscillations (Fig. 5). To complement the UV–vis spectrophotometer measurements, analysis of the changes in fluorescent properties of the OC, i.e., relatively higher BIX, FI, and % C3 and lower HIX indices, provide additional evidence for the presence of more microbial-derived C after 2nd vs 1st RO events. In contrast to plant-derived C, microbial-derived C is often depleted in aromatic C (< 15 %) (Chin et al., 1994; Weishaar et al., 2003) with lower HIX and higher BIX values (Xu and Guo, 2017). The release of high aromatic C compounds following the 1st RO events suggests a greater contribution of lignin-derived OC likely from vascular plant materials (Engelhaupt and Bianchi, 2001). The re-oxidaiton of the soil columns after the 1st RO event could influence the formation of organo-mineral complexes by 1) rapidly resetting the redox state of the reduced OM that formed during the 1st anoxic-half cycle event and 2) enhancing the formation of short-range ordered (SRO) or crystalline Fe oxides (Chen and Thompson, 2018; Chen et al., 2018; Schwertmann and Taylor, 1989). Although we do not have any direct evidence on Fe crystallinity from Mössbauer-Spectroscopy, we expect an overall increase in Fe crystallinity following the 2nd RO event, which has been observed by Thompson et al. (2006b) in slurry systems. The shifts in crystallinity of Fe oxides and molecular composition of OC are indications for redox-driven changes in organo-mineral associaitons in soil, which can impact the stability and mobility of OC. Such variations in the molecular composition of OC indicate alternating processes governing the stabilization of SOM. For example, a single RO cycle can decrease preferential sorption/attachment of plant-derived compounds to mineral surfaces resulting in the migration of these OC components deeper into the subsoil. In contrast, repeated redox oscillations tend to favor the mobilization of microbial metabolites from the topsoil layer. Such heterogeneity in the properties of released OC in response to the sequence of redox oscillations has significant implications for the fate and transport of soil OC to downstream ecosystems and groundwater aquifer as well as in our understanding and accurate assessment of global C cycling.

The detected increase in the fine colloid and particulate OC fractions (i.e., >100 nm) from 7 % to 40 % between 1st and 2nd RO events indirectly confirms the clustering of nanoaggregates as well as the formation of more colloidal size nanoaggregates in soil (Fig. 4, Fig. 5, Fig. 6). Similar aggregation of nano or colloid particles with increasing redox oscillations was previously observed in a batch incubation study (Afsar et al., 2020). Nanoaggregates are approximately 100 nm in diameter (Calabi-Floody et al., 2011; Huang et al., 2016) that can stabilize OC within the soil aggregates and allow long-term C sequestration in soil (Chevallier et al., 2010; Lehmann et al., 2007; Six et al., 2000). They can also act as a composite building unit of microaggregates (Asano and Wagai, 2014; Kögel-Knabner et al., 2008; Lehmann et al., 2007; Totsche et al., 2018), where microbial-derived C can act as a bridging agent to stabilize nano and colloid-sized organo-mineral associations in soil (Asano and Wagai, 2015; Mikutta et al., 2007). The formation of nanoaggregates enriched with microbial-derived C following redox oscillation is in good agreement with the conceptual three-dimensional functional view of C turnover dynamics as proposed by Kleber and Johnson (2010). This more recent view suggests that independent mineral-OM microaggregates form around microbial metabolites or cells. In contrast, the prior two-dimensional concept implies that soil OM accumulates uniformly on soil mineral surfaces through sorption, which can then act as a backbone for accumulating additional layers of OM with different molecular compositions (Possinger et al., 2020).

5. Conclusions

While translating results from laboratory experiments to the natural environment is always challenging, our controlled incubation study may provide a baseline to predict how organo-mineral associations may revolve around the redox-dependent biogeochemical processes in soil. Oscillating oxic-anoxic events are induced by variations in soil moisture and O2 conditions that are very common in wetlands, humid tropical soils, plant-root interfaces, vadose zones, and paddy soils. Our study demonstrates that redox oscillations can significantly alter size-dependent heterogeneity in both the concentration and molecular composition of mobile soil OC. The observed increase in the formation of nano and microaggregates that are enriched in microbial-derived OC following redox oscillations provide insight into changes in C stabilization mechanisms under oscillating oxic-anoxic conditions. The release of the less aromatic C, indicative of microbial metabolites following cumulative RO events, further suggests that C reaction dynamics and cycling in a transition zone would vary significantly from the upland (e.g., with prolonged oxic conditions) and wetland (e.g., with mostly anoxic conditions) zones in a seasonally flooded wetland. Additionally, OC in colloidal fraction, which has a different composition from the dissolved fraction, could be a significant part of the global C pool in redox-fluctuating environments. The size-dependent variations in OC concentration and composition during successive redox oscillations could have significant implications for the fate and transport of SOM to downstream ecosystems and groundwater aquifers as well as in the understanding and accurate assessment of global C cycling. Our findings support the ecosystem perspective that the persistence of SOM does not solely depend on SOM's intrinsic properties; it also depends strongly on the surrounding environmental conditions. Results from this study provide clear evidence for size-dependent heterogeneity in soil OC, particularly within cut-off size ranges of traditional “dissolved” fractions. Such knowledge will improve our ability to better assess and predict the environmental and ecological role of OC in terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems as well as the effects of ongoing climate change on the turnover of soil OC in redox-sensitive environments such as wetlands.
